Not an answer, just a note, you can access the angular scope with javascript as angular is already in the page, create/edit new/existing mailing and try this in the browser console: `var scope = angular.element('[ng-controller="MsgTemplateCtrl"]').scope(); scope.$watch('mailing.msg_template_id', function(){
 console.log(scope.mailing.msg_template_id);
});` with __scope.mailing__ you can access and listen to the mailing params, I guess you already know it but if you enable debug and add `?angularDebug` at the end of the url you will see a new accordion with the params, hope that helps somehow

